full_text:
JAM was a hub. If you were doing
something imaginative, creative,
off-center, fresh, and Black, you
would gravitate toward JAM.
Linda wanted the artists involved
with the gallery to be those
who were pushing themselves to
go somewhere new.
Pat Cummings, JAM assistant director and children's book author and illustrator
I remember being at the apart-
ment Linda shared with her kids
and her brother. Faythe Weaver,
Pat Cummings, and I were sitting
and strategizing with Linda
about what we would now call
"branding" and "public relations."
Lowery Stokes Sims, JAM volunteer, art historian, and curator
